                                        <section class="spotlight">
                                                      <div class="image">
                                                                <img src="http://res.cloudinary.com/henix/image/upload/v1463793365/djn85ngx-1446604577lol_nctpgg.jpg" alt="" /></div>
                                                                <div class="content">
                                                                          <h2>First perception</h2>
                                                                          <p>Multiculturalism can be simply described as a “demographic descriptor of diverse population” (Western Sydney University, 2015), which is the most common use of the word. Mainly, in European countries which recognize the ethno-cultural. Moreover, the German, French, British, Dutch and some other European leaders appear to have one thing in common; when they use the multiculturalism word, they actually mean Islamic culture. (Western Sydney University, 2015)</p>
                                                      </div>
                                        </section>
                                        <section class="spotlight">
                                                      <div class="image">
                                                                <img src="http://res.cloudinary.com/henix/image/upload/v1463793356/djn85ngx-1446604577_dnha7n.jpg" alt="" /></div>
                                                                <div class="content">
                                                                          <h2>Second perception</h2>
                                                                          <p>Nevertheless, multiculturalism can also be used as a “normative ideal ideological concept” (Western Sydney University, 2015) about how a diverse society should be organized to be a just. It assumes that culture is enriched by diversity rather than polluted by it and that the diverse cultural elements exist within a cultural envelope that creates its own common ground. (Western Sydney University, 2015)</p>
                                                      </div>
                                        </section>
                                        <section class="spotlight">
                                                      <div class="image">
                                                                <img src="http://res.cloudinary.com/henix/image/upload/v1463793350/djn85ngx-144660457lol7_bw9pzj.jpg" alt="" /></div>
                                                                <div class="content">
                                                                          <h2>Third perception</h2>
                                                                          <p>And finally, there is the multiculturalism which is understood as a “social contract that involves power and wealth sharing between different ethno-cultural groups” (Western Sydney University, 2015). It usually consists of a complex set of agreed national values and goals, normative and structural systems as well as policy, budgetary and program responses put in place to manage diversity. Multiculturalism in this sense is recognized in countries such as Canada, New Zealand and Australia. (Western Sydney University, 2015)</p>
                                                      </div>
                                        </section>
                            </section>
                            
                            <!--Three-->
                            <section id="three" class="wrapper style3 special">
                                        <div class="inner">
                                                  <header class="major">
                                                               <h2>Australia: a multicultural inheritance</h2>
                                                               <p>Australia has always been a society with culturally diverse elements. Prior to permanent European settlement in 1788 there were many different indigenous cultures. Most people who came to Australia in the 18th and 19th centuries were from the British Isles, there were others from a variety of backgrounds. The gold rush of the 1850s attracted people from all over the world.
                                                               Since World War II, approximately 6 million immigrants from over 150 countries are settled in Australia (Members of the National Multicultural Advisory Council, 1997). Today, around 41 per cent of people living in Australia were born overseas or have a parent born overseas. These percentages are among the highest in the developed world. Collectively, there are approximately 260 languages spoken in Australia. (The Australian Collaboration, 2013).</p>
                                                  </header>
                                                  <ul class="features">
                                                           <li>
                                                                 <h3>Cultural identity</h3>
                                                                 									<p>“The right of all Australians, within carefully defined limits, to express and share their individual cultural heritage, including their language and religion.” (Member of the National Multicultural Advisory Council, 1997).</p>
                                                           </li>
                                                           <li>
                                                                 <h3>Social justice</h3>
                                                                 									<p>“The right of all Australians to equality of treatment and opportunity, and the removal of barriers of race, ethnicity, culture, religion, language, gender or place of birth.” (Member of the National Multicultural Advisory Council, 1997).
</p>
                                                           </li>
                                                           <li>       
                                                                <h3>Economy</h3>
                                                                 									<p>About half of all workers added to the Australian labour market in the past six decades are immigrants. In recent years, immigration policy has been adjusted to give preference to business migration skilled and professionally educated. Migrants in the midst of business, who speak other languages and understand other cultures, has helped business and trade in Australia. They are able to help to open up markets in other overseas countries. (Skwirk Online Education, n.a).</p>
                                                           </li>
                                                           <li>
                                                                 <h3>Cultures</h3>
                                                                 									<p>“Australia is one of the most multi-faith, multi-lingual, and multi-cultural countries in the world” (National Cultural Diversity Committee, d.a). The Australian constitution protects an individual’s right to practice any religions which allows people to celebrate them openly. 
                                                                    Considering food, there are more restaurants all around the world available with the opportunity to discover new flavor. In the same way about music and dances and the possibility to learn and practice as if you were in the concerned country. As a consequence there are many cultural events like international food days, cultural dances, plays, art, music, spiritualities and more. </p>
                                                           </li>
                                                            <li>
                                                                 <h3>Social cohesion</h3>
                                                                 									<p>Through multiculturalism, the Australian experience has shown that diversity lead to a strong social cohesion. Multiculturalism has been an important element in the making of modern Australia, (Australian Human Rights Commission, 2014). For instance in the food industry, diversity enhances the bond and social interaction between different culture, it is often a strong point for meetings and celebrations. Also, in the education sector which encourage thought multicultural and open-mindness to discovering and learning.</p>
                                                           </li>
                                                           <li>
                                                                 <h3>Benefits</h3>
                                                                 									<p>The impact of diversity touches every aspect of the way Australians live and work. Culturally diverse communities can have positive or negative effects depending on how it was managed. Properly managed, it provides social and economic benefits for the whole community; badly managed it can give rise to conflict and disintegration. (Australian Government, 2014).</p>
                                                           </li>
                                                          
                                                  </ul>
                                        </div>
                            </section>
                            
                            <!--CTA-->
                            <section id="cta" class="wrapper style4">
                                       <div class="inner">
                                                 <header>
                                                         <h2>Conclusion</h2>
                                                         								<p>To summarize, people of all religions, ethnic backgrounds, age and gender have much to contribute, but this can only happen when there is a sense of inclusion and belonging, when people feel part of this country (Australian Human Rights Commission, 2014). Therefore, Australia benefits significantly by being a multicultural society: economically, socially, the recognition and appreciation of diversity and building of a modern nation. </p>
                                                 </header>
                                       </div>
